I spent every day of my teens womping in the shadow of the Venice Pier with my friends, when it was only a spot for us bodysurfers, and all the surfers hit the Breakwater. 
(Times changed, Venice changed, surf cams came along and now I’m usually the only finned weirdo out there among all the fiberglass. )
When the recently formed  @venicesurfingassociation asked me to design the inaugural poster for next week’s Southside Classic surf contest, I jumped at the chance to give a little something back to the spot that’s given me so much. What an honor. 
Long live the Venice Pier, in all her evolutions. See you down there next week!
Oh and support the @venicesurfingassociation they’re doing great work.

This is a little story about a big snake. His name was Happy, and for 33 years he was there next to me, from city to city and chapter to chapter. Now, 33 years (basically my entire adult life) is an extremely long life for a snake, but I wish he’d made it to 34. He never bit, he rarely hissed, he showed my daughters and friends that maybe snakes weren’t so bad after all, and he was the sweetest African Rock python ever. 
Laugh all you want at getting sentimental over losing a snake, but as far as I’m concerned snakes are people too. Maybe better. And Happy was the best. 
You were always there Happy, and I wish you still were. Thanks for keeping this weirdo’s heart full, and I’ll never forget you. See you down the road. 
.
